Here is a JavaScript function that takes in text and formats it by adding a new line after each sentence:

```
function formatText(text) {
  return text.replace(/\. /g, '.\n');
}
```

This function uses the `replace()` method to replace each occurrence of a period followed by a space with a period and a new line character (`\n`). The `g` flag makes the replacement global, meaning it will replace all occurrences in the text. 

To use the function, simply call it with the text you want to format as an argument:

```
let myText = "This is a sentence. This is another sentence. And here is one more.";
let formattedText = formatText(myText);
console.log(formattedText);
```

This will output the formatted text:

```
This is a sentence.
This is another sentence.
And here is one more.
```

