Here's a JavaScript function that appends a new line character to a string if it ends with a dot or a question mark:

```
function appendNewline(text) {
  if (/\.\s*$|\?\s*$/.test(text)) {
    return text + "\n";
  } else {
    return text;
  }
}
```

This function checks if the input string ends with a dot or a question mark and zero or more whitespace characters (`\s*`). This is done using a regular expression `/\.+\s*$|\?+\s*$/`. 

If the regular expression matches (i.e. the input string ends with a dot or a question mark), the function appends a new line character to the string and returns it. Otherwise, it returns the unchanged input string.

To use the function, simply call it with the text you want to format as an argument:

```
let myText = "This is a sentence.";
let formattedText = appendNewline(myText);
console.log(formattedText);
```

This will output the formatted text with a newline character at the end:

```
This is a sentence.
```

Note that if the input string already ends with a new line, the function will append a second new line character. If you want to avoid this behavior, you can modify the regular expression to exclude whitespace characters from the match:

```
function appendNewline(text) {
  if (/\.\s*$|\?\s*$/.test(text)) {
    return text + (text.endsWith('\n') ? '' : '\n');
  } else {
    return text;
  }
}
```

This version of the function checks if the input string ends with a new line character (`\n`) before appending a new line. If the input string already ends with a new line, it only returns the original input string without adding an extra new line character.
